Cosimo I de' Medici (1519–1574), Duke of Florence|https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/207699|] In 1534, in rivalry with Michelangelo, Baccio Bandinelli carved the colossal Hercules and Cacus, a marble group that confronted the older sculptor’s famous David (finished in 1504) on the Piazza della Signoria in Florence. With their stiff postures and lapidary precision, the figures of Bandinelli’s group could not compete in grace and power with Michelangelo’s youth. Over the years, Bandinelli created a unique, even idiosyncratic, Mannerist style (the style prevalent in Italy after the 1520s) and achieved considerable success, yet constantly strove to emerge from  ...    eighteen-year-old Cosimo de’ Medici became duke of Florence in 1537, the sculptor found increasing favor in his native  ...    works, is meant to make Cosimo appear decisive; it appropriately echoes the pose of Michelangelo’s Giuliano de’ Medici,  ...    robe of rank — have ancient imperial associations. From the beginning of his reign Cosimo was particularly eager to be  ...    - Medium: Marble - Culture: Italian,
